<html><HEAD><TITLE>Duplantier:  DO-GOODERS BENT ON CONTROLLING OTHERS</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a><center><h4>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </h4><i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br><a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a> <br>November 27, 1995<br></i><hr><h2>Do-Gooders Bent on Controlling Others</h2></center><P>                                     
[They're convinced they can solve all the world's problems if we just do 
what they say. No matter how messed up their own lives are, no matter 
how much they disrupt the lives of others, those dauntless do-gooders 
never stop believing that they know what's best for the rest of us.]
<p>
The do-gooders jump from cause to cause, dictating solutions that betray 
ignorance of the problem at hand and total disregard for the consequences 
of their proposals. They don't seem to care whether their policies and 
practices really work or not. Why, then, do they do what they do? <p>Don't 
let their lofty rhetoric fool you. What do-gooders are really after, says 
syndicated columnist Thomas Sowell of the Hoover Institution, is "ego 
gratification " By making us feel bad, they make themselves feel good.
<p>
Sowell cites many examples. "Recycling, drug education, sex education, 
animal rights, gun control, multiculturalism. environmentalism and 
innumerable other social crusades produce far more benefits to the 
crusaders than for society,. In many cases, they make society worse off," 
says Sowell. "Studies have repeatedly shown recycling does more harm 
than good, and much evidence suggests that the actual consequences of 
both drug education and sex education are nil, at best."
<p>
Do-gooders don't care if recycling causes more ecological damage than 
the original manufacturing process. They don't care if drug and sex 
education programs encourage experimentation. They don't care if gun 
control increases violence. They don't care if multiculturalism 
exacerbates racial tensions. Do-gooders don't care how things really 
work, or what the truth is. Their sole concern is to "make a statement." As 
Sowell points out. "there is no need to check out facts if the real point is 
moral preening."
<p>
Do-gooders have plagued mankind with their coercive correctives for 
hundreds of years. "In the l 9th century, housing reform in the cities was 
the big crusade," says Sowell, "especially in the slums occupied by 
recently arrived immigrants. Though many immigrants lived in crowded 
quarters in run-down neighborhoods because they had no choice, others 
doubled up and scrimped to save money to send to their families back in 
the old country. Some saved to prepare for a better future."
<p>
It's too bad that the do-gooders couldn't leave well enough alone, but it's 
in their nature to interfere. They felt compelled to save those poor souls 
from themselves. "Reformers decided that people needed more space per 
person and wrote that into laws, thereby raising the cost of housing to the 
immigrants," says Sowell. "People were forced to spend their money not 
on what their own top priorities were, but on what the anointed 
busybodies decided was best for them."
<p>
Such meddling has gone on for millennia. Sowell understands the 
syndrome and accepts it as a fact of life, observing that "the real question 
is not why some people treat public policy as exercises in ego 
gratification. The question is why the rest of us listen to them so 
gullibly."
<p>                           <P><i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i><p><br><br><center><br><a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a></center></body></html>
