<html><HEAD><TITLE>Duplantier:  REAL MEN</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<center><h4>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </h4><i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a> <br>
December 12, 1995
<br></i><hr>
<h2>Real Men</h2></center><P> 
[Remember the good old days when men were the towers of strength and 
faithfulness we expected them to be?]
<P>
Tens of thousands of American males are trying to rediscover what it 
really means to be a man, and thousands of American women are rooting 
for them. Syndicated columnist Armstrong Williams reports that a group 
called Promise Keepers is "attracting men of all backgrounds to publicly 
declare their faith in God and acceptance of responsibility for leadership 
in their families and communities." Promise Keepers have filled football 
stadiums to demonstrate their determination to keep their marriage 
promises. What's behind it? Why is it happening now? Williams believes 
that, after three decades of experimentation it's become indisputably 
clear that the deconstruction of traditional gender roles by the feminist 
and the playboy movements has failed.
<P>
"After more than a quarter-century that saw the rise of feminism, gay 
rights, and societal approval of a variety of so-called 'alternative 
lifestyles,' we have come almost full circle," says Williams. "The results 
of our cultural experimentation -- high divorce and illegitimacy rates, 
rising crime and violence -- have forced us to take a second look. 
Perhaps the traditional male role as a leader of the family and 
community, should be restored."
<P>
There's little doubt about that, of course. The big question is, How many 
young American males can even remember what it means to be a real 
man? Not many, concludes Williams, who offers a refresher course. 
Being a real man means respecting "the institution of marriage" and 
being responsible for the children that you bring into the world. It means 
scrupulosity in word and deed. "A real man has no need for profanity 
[and] does not engage in public disorderliness or drunkenness. A real 
man accepts responsibility for his actions; he does not make excuses for 
his mistakes or failures. He learns from them and improves himself to 
ensure that they do not happen again."
<P>
A real man is always conscious of the impression he makes, knowing 
that he is "an example and role model for his own children and the 
children in his neighborhood." He is honest, bold, and resolute. "That 
means making a decision consistent with your principles and sticking to 
it," says Williams. "A real man knows that showing love is not a 
weakness, but a strength." He understands the difference between men 
and women, accepts it, celebrates it. At the risk of being denounced for 
his gallantry, he holds doors open for women and gives up his seat on 
the bus for them.
<P>
A man must have "integrity," says Armstrong Williams, and that means 
"holding on to your principles regardless of the circumstances." A lot of 
men need these lessons in manhood, Armstrong says, because Americans 
"have forgotten where we came from and so we don't know where we're 
going. Only by remembering how things once were will we be able to 
begin working to restore civility and virtue to our chaotic society." Three 
cheers for the Promise Keepers!
<p>                           <P>
<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i><p><br><br><center><br><a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a></center></body></html>
