<HTML>
<TITLE>Guest Columnists </title>

<hr>
<center><h2>Fetal Tissue Consumption/Research</h2>
 By<br><a href="/townhall/columnists/howley.html"> Kathleen Howley </a></center>
 <p>
 <hr>
 <P>
 

     News from the world of medicine: Chinese doctors think they have 
discovered something that cures asthma, restores health, and, at the 
same time, makes skin look years younger. 
<P>
     And, there's an abundant supply, which keeps the price down.
<P>
     Sounds too good to be true? Wait 'till you hear the rest. 
<P>
     The Eastern Express, an English-language newspaper in Hong Kong, 
broke the story on April 12, with details of the burgeoning practice 
of selling the bodies of aborted children, to be used as health food. 
Since then, the story has been picked up by the Wall Street Journal, 
the Washington Times, United Press International, and it's been shown 
on CNN. 
<P>
     Now, Republicans are demanding that the Clinton administration 
investigate, and they're planning to hold hearings in the House of 
Representatives.
<P>
     Rep. Frank R. Wolf, a Republican from Virginia, said the new 
allegations could result in a Congressional call for the United States 
to revoke "Most Favored Nation" trade status for China -- a privilege 
granted by President Clinton despite the manifold allegations of human 
rights abuses in China.
<P>
     This is a nauseating topic -- true. But it's a story that needs 
to be told, just as the shocking crimes of the Holocaust needed to be 
laid bare for the world to see.
<P>
     Zou Qin, 32, a doctor at the Luo Hu abortuary in Shenzhen, China, 
told the Eastern Express reporter that she has eaten more than 100 
fetuses in the past six months, and described them as "highly 
nutritious." The story included a picture of her holding a jar 
containing the tiny body of an aborted child.
<P>
     The doctor said: 
<P>
     "They are wasted if we don't eat them. The women who receive 
abortions here don't want the fetuses. Also, the fetuses are already 
dead (when we eat them). We don't carry out abortions just to eat the 
fetuses."
<P>
     Sound familiar? That's the same argument used by Sen. Ted 
Kennedy, Rep. Joseph Kennedy, and cohorts, to justify fetal research 
in America. 
<P>
     So, before you allow the shock to settle in, ask yourself: what's 
the difference? The Chinese are eating unborn children as health food. 
We're cannibalizing their body parts in the name of "science." 
<P>
     And, during the presidential campaign, Clinton used the same 
logic as Dr. Zou Qin, almost verbatim, when he was asked whether he 
supported experimenting on aborted humans. 
<P>
     They'd only go to waste, Clinton said. Fetal research is going to 
help people and relieve their suffering, he said. No one bothered to 
ask him: at what cost?
<P>
     In fact, one of Clinton's first acts after being sworn in as 
president was to revoke the ban on using tax dollars to fund fetal 
research. That's right: your hard-earned money is being used, right 
now, to pay for it.
<P>
     But, when fetal research is reported on the network news in 
America, it's with a positive spin. The film footage typically shows 
sufferers who allegedly have been restored to health after undergoing 
treatment that involved the injection of fetal brain cells into their 
damaged brains. 
<P>
     Not one word about the tiny human beings who were used, without 
their consent, as donors.
<P>
     Like the Chinese, scientists in America prefer older, more 
developed fetuses. The Eastern Express story reported that full-term 
fetuses were more desirable and more expensive in China -- because 
they were considered more nutritious.  
<P>
     In the world of Western medical research, mature fetuses are more 
desirable, too, because the organs are more developed. 
<P>
     There's one difference, though. The Chinese use dead babies. In 
America, some of the experimentation involves removing parts from live 
babies, before killing and aborting them. 
<P>
     If you have a hard time believing that, read the scientific 
papers that describe the procedures. Or, just ask yourself: would any 
doctor inject dead fetal brain cells into the brain of a Parkinson's 
sufferer? No. The brain cells have to be living, or they're no good.
<P>
     Could any dead fetal organs be used in medical experiments that 
involve transplantation into living adults? No. 
<P>
     Or, ask yourself: would any fetal body parts be usable after 
being subjected to a standard abortion procedure? Once again, the 
answer is, no.
<P>
     So, before we get on our high horse and start pointing at the 
Chinese in disgust, let's remember what we tolerate in America.
<P>
     In the end, the blame doesn't rest solely with the American 
researchers who do the grisly deeds. It also rests on the people who 
allow it to happen, by looking the other way.
<P>
     If you're inflamed by what's going on in China, take some of that 
indignation and use it to combat cannibalism on our own soil. Speak 
for those who have no voice.
<P>
            

<I>Kathleen Howley is a syndicated columnist<BR>
Copyright 1994, Living Word Syndicate<BR>

<BR></I>
