<head>
<title>Walt Disney Co. -Porn pushers</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<hr>
<center>
<h2>Walt Disney Co. - Porn pushers</h2>


By<br><a href="/townhall/columnists/howley.html"> Kathleen Howley</a>
</center><p>
<hr>
<p>
Wall Street was dazzled by the recent $19 billion merger of Walt 
Disney Company and Capital Cities/ABC -- the second-largest take-over 
in history. 
<p>
Pundits said it was a good deal for the American entertainment 
industry. But, something tells me that 'ol Walt is rolling over in his 
grave.  
<p>
Not because ABC has a reputation for in-your-face bad taste. Yes, 
these are the people who gave us the jaw-dropping venom of Roseanne, 
and the steaming story lines of NYPD Blue, billed as television's 
first R-rated series. 
<p>
And, you'll notice that through it all, ABC continues to bill 
themselves as the "family station." 
<p>
But, the problem isn't with ABC. It's with Disney. 
<p>
When it comes to down-and-dirty porn pushers, you won't find many who 
have stooped as low as the Walt Disney Company has over the past year. 
<p>
No, I'm not talking about the R-rated anti-Catholic movie "Priest," 
described in one magazine as having "the best gay sex scenes in a non-
pornographic film."  
<p>
It's much worse than that. It's a movie called "Kids," recently 
released by Disney's wholly-owned subsidiary, Miramax -- the same 
people who gave us "Priest." 
<p>
It details the sexual experiences of 13- to 16-year-old New York 
teenagers. And, it's not a pretty picture.  
<p>
According to Reuters and the Associated Press, even a few hard-to-faze 
movie reviewers looked a bit taken aback as they left a pre-release 
showing at the Cannes film festival several months ago.  
<p>
One critic branded it "kiddie porn." The board who rates Hollywood 
movies agreed with him. 
<p>
They gave it an NC-17 rating, the new category that means not quite an 
X-rated movie, but almost. Miramax, fearing the stigma of an NC-17 
rating, chose to release the film unrated, which means it won't be 
running in as many theaters, but will still make the full rounds of 
video stores in its afterlife. 
<p>
The film opens with the main character, a promiscuous skateboarding 
teen named Telly, having sex with a 14-year-old girl. Later, he 
relates the entire scene in vulgar details to his buddy. As it turns 
out, seducing virgins is Telly's idea of "safe sex." 
<p>
It gets worse. Reviewers report that during a party sequence filled 
with explicit sex, a teenage girl passes out, high on drugs, and is 
raped by one of Telly's friends. 
<p>
Yes, that's right. This is the Walt Disney Company we're talking about 
-- the same people who created "101 Dalmations."  
<p>
Now, they've joined the lowest segment of the America media, intent on 
warping the minds of teenagers by linking sex with violence. 
<p>
"Kids" is showing in major cities across the country. And, it's a 
qualified hit. When it premiered, it broke the house records for 
weekend box office grosses at two New York City theaters.  
<p>
There have been a few naysayers, but most reviewers have been positive 
-- probably the same ones who praised "Priest."  
<p>
First-time director Larry Clark, 53, is getting plenty of media 
attention for "Kids." A July 26 profile in the New York Times 
reported: "The success of the film is allowing Mr. Clark to plan 
future movies."  
<p>
The profile doesn't mention Clark's well-documented background as a 
kiddie porn photographer. You have to read a publication such as the 
July issue of the "American Family Association Journal" to get the 
revolting details on that. (P.O. Drawer 2440, Tupelo, MS 38803) 
<p>
Clark is already talking about beginning his next film, which will 
focus on kids, sex, and suicide -- a theme that reoccurs in many of 
his porn photographs. He says he sees the new film as part two of a 
trilogy. 
<p>
So, why is Disney giving a platform to a psychopath? Because Clark's 
film is going to make money. That's why Disney dropped its standards 
almost a decade ago and began making R-rated films, hiding behind 
subsidiary companies. The long list of Disney-funded R-rated films 
seems tame, now, compared to their new ventures. 
<p>
Money. That's all that interests Disney chairman Michael Eisner, 
described by the New York Times as "one of the most ferociously 
ambitious people in Hollywood." 
<p>
Money enough to buy a television network, and create a media empire. 
Money enough to earn Eisner more than $10 million in salary and 
bonuses last year. 
<p>
Poor Mickey. Once, he was the most respectable mouse in the world. 
Now, he works for a porn pusher. 
 <p>
 <i>Kathleen Howley is a syndicated columnist<br> 
 Copyright 1995, Living Word Syndicate</i> 
 <p>

<br>
<center>
