<head>
<title>Did My Parents Want Me</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<hr>
<center>
<h2>Did My Parents WANT Me?</h2>
By<br><a href="/townhall/columnists/howley.html">Kathleen Howley</a>
</center>
<hr>
<br>
A woman, in her mid-40s, recently told me that she grew up with the 
feeling that her parents didn't want her.<p>  
She said she overheard, one night, a comment made by her mother, who 
didn't realize that little ears were listening. It referred to the 
conception of her daughter as being the result of "one drink too 
many." <p> 
It was meant as a joke. And, my friend reports that all the adults who 
heard it laughed. But she wasn't laughing.  <p>
In fact, that one comment, with perhaps, the subtle reinforcement of 
other stray remarks, haunted her for years. <p>
Oh, sure, her parents fed her and clothed her and sent her to school, 
and even went to "parent/teacher" nights -- the things that to all the 
world make people look like loving and caring parents. <p>
And, for all I know, they could have been exactly that. My friend 
wouldn't have disputed that possibility.  <p>
But, she wasn't talking about the love that almost any normal adult 
can learn to feel about a cute and cuddly baby.  <p>
She was talking about the deep-down questions that all children ponder 
as they learn about the world they live in:  <p>
When I was called into being, when I was created, did my parents WANT 
me? When I was thrust into this strange, new world, was there someone 
yearning for my arrival?  <p>
Somehow, if the answer to that question is , "Yes," it makes 
everything else easier. It covers a multitude of later lapses and 
human failings.  <p>
I suppose that it's much like arriving at the door of an important 
party knowing that you are an invited guest, as compared to walking 
toward the front steps without an invitation.  <p>
Of course, we all know that the most important Being of all, the 
Creator of the Universe, wanted each and every one of us to be born.  <p>
In fact, it's more than that. The Father not only loved us and called 
us into being. He also gave each of us a crucial job to do during our 
lifetime on earth -- a job that, whether great or small, is infinitely 
important in His plan. <p>
In adult life, that fact can be a great comfort. But, it seems that 
children need more.  <p>
Today, we live in a world that is ruled with a contraceptive 
mentality. It's a stingy philosophy that says, yes, children are a 
good thing, but only give me, at most, two of them. Any more than 
that, and they become a bad thing. <p>
How, I wonder, do today's children feel, growing up in a family with 
the knowledge that they barely made it under the wire. Just two. No 
more. We have no more love to give. <p>
Even if you're number one or two, you know that the love you receive 
from your parents is conditional. "We love you, because you happen to 
arrive when you did." <p>
Someone was ranting to me, recently, that people shouldn't have more 
than two children. <p>
I asked her: <p>
"Where do you fall in the birth order of your family?" <p>
She answered: <p>
"I'm the fourth child." <p>
Good thing her parents didn't agree with her ideas. Else, she never 
would have existed. <p>
I'm the second child in my family. Lucky me. I would have been born, 
even if my parents subscribed to a contraceptive mentality. Although, 
my little sisters would have been left out in the cold. <p>
Fortunately, I have the great gift of knowing that my parents wanted 
as many children as God would give them. That gave us Howley kids a 
jump start in life. We were wanted, yearned for, rejoiced over. Every 
one of us. <p>
But what about today's children, who live in families that have a 
stingy attitude toward life? Maybe God wanted more. Maybe He intended 
that third kid to be one who introduced the first kid to the woman he 
would marry, or got a job for kid number two when he got out of 
college. Or, maybe it was that fifth kid who was going to care for the 
parents when they were elderly. <p>
The fact is, it's not unconditional love for a couple to use chemicals 
to ensure that only one or two children are born. You can argue that 
it shows greater love to have just two children, and be able to 
provide them with every material asset. The best kindergarten, the 
best college.  <p>
Problem is, maybe they won't want to go to college. Maybe they'd 
prefer to have a brother, rather than a new car for their high school 
graduation. <p>
Mother Theresa said it best. In news accounts, she was quoted as 
saying, "In America, children have every material thing, but they are 
very lonely, because they don't have brothers or sisters to play 
with." <p>
So, when you have that third child, or fourth, or more, and people 
start raising eyebrows, asking, "How MANY are you going to have?" -- 
just answer, " I don't know, you'll have to ask God. He has a plan." <p>
<br>
<i>Kathleen Howley is a syndicated columnist<br>
Copyright 1995, Living Word Syndicate <p>
 Internet:73360.271@compuserve.com</i><p>
