<html>
<title>Politics Makes Strange Bedfellow</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<hr>
<center><h3>Politics Makes Strange Bedfellows</h3><br>
By<br><a href="townhall/columnists/howley.html"> Kathleen Howley</a><p>
<hr></center> 
<P>
 
The fat lady has yet to sing. With Democrats continuing to desert 
their party in droves, especially on the state level, the political 
drubbing that began with the November elections is going into extra 
innings. 
<P>
Almost every week, the newspapers carry stories of Democrats who have 
decided either to switch, or to quit. 
<P>
The political concept of Liberalism -- spelled with a capital "L" -- 
is dead, at least for this millennium. No longer will government 
simply give handouts as the solution to every problem. No longer can 
the media merrily assume to represent the views of all Americans when 
they postulate that freedom in America equals life without values. 
<P>
But, before Republican leaders get too euphoric about the all-out 
rout, it would be wise to remember that politics makes strange 
bedfellows.  
<P>
Some of their staunchest supports today are people who don't really 
fit into the Republican party, or the Democratic party. They are 
called: Catholic voters. 
<P>
 Of the 250 million people in America, 95 million, or two out of every 
five, are Roman Catholic. Sure, some of them have fallen away from the 
faith, for now -- after all, the Church has not been immune from the 
devastating effects of the "Just-Me" philosophy that hit society in 
the 1960s.  
<P>
 But, despite the biased polls you'll occasionally see in the 
newspapers, most remain firm supporters of Catholic teachings 
regarding the value of life and the family. 
<P>
 At the moment, the Republicans are best representing their views. 
Forty years ago, it was the Democrats. The mass of Catholic voters 
switched once. They can switch again. 
<P>
 Probably, that doesn't make too many Republicans quake in their 
boots. Of the two parties, they are the most pro-life, they'll tell 
you. They have the best ideas for restoring the strength of the 
family. They have a common-sense and value-based approach to 
education.  
<P>
 But, every once in a while, an issue comes along that makes the 
typical Catholic voter extremely ill-at-ease with the standard 
Republican party line. 
<P>
Immigration is one -- in a big way. Most Catholic voters are 
descendants of turn-of-the-century immigrants. True, it makes good 
sense to secure our borders and to crack down on illegal immigration -
- as long as that doesn't mean punishing the innocent children of 
illegals. 
<P>
 However, many Catholics will tell you that America must never close 
her doors to legal immigration, or develop a stingy attitude toward 
it, lest we lose our vigor and make a lie of the Statue of Liberty: 
"Give me your tired, your poor, your huddled masses yearning to breath 
free." 
<P>
 And, here's another issue: immoral labor practices. 
<P>
 No, I'm not going to hop on the media bandwagon and tell you that the 
big, bad Republicans only care about making a buck. I'm not going to 
even mention country clubs.  
<P>
 But, the fact is, the Republican party seems ever-ready to put the 
laborer at the mercy of the corporate decision-makers. If they want to 
hold on to their Catholic supporters, they are going to have to knock 
it off. 
<P>
  During recent months, the National Labor Committee in New York has 
sponsored a cross-country tour for two teenagers to tell the world of 
their experiences in the garment sweatshops of Honduras and El 
Savador, assembling high-priced clothes for The Gap, Banana Republic, 
Eddie Bauer, Sears, and Gitano, a subsidiary of Fruit of the Loom. 
<P>
  In these tax-free factories, built specifically to produce goods for 
the U.S. and Canadian markets, children and young women work shifts 
that sometimes exceed18 hours, for below-subsistence wages. The abuses 
they recount are mind-numbing. 
<P>
 Of course, the corporate bigwigs deny all of it. But, if you ask me 
who I'm going to believe -- Donald Fisher, who was paid more than $2 
million last year to run the Gap empire, or Judith Viera, an 18-year-
old who made 56 cents an hour and was limited to two bathroom trips a 
shift --- hummm....who would you believe? 
<P>
Judith, by the way, was fired when she tried to help organize a union. 
For good measure, the big boss also threw out her three sisters, just 
because they were related. 
<P>
 On her last 18-hour shift on the production line, Judith said they 
were sewing Eddie Bauer T-shirts. The crew included two workers who 
were only 15 years old. 
<P>
 Earlier this year, the House's Trade Subcommitee approved a bill 
introduced by Republican Phillip Crane to increase the tariff breaks 
for products entering the U.S. from sweatshops in the Central American 
and the Caribbean by $240 million.  
<P>
 Remember the giant sucking sound? H.R. 553 means it will only get 
louder, with more American companies being wooed by the prospects of 
33-cents-an-hour wages and laborers who are vulnerable to 
exploitation. 
<P>
 Currently, the bill has been set aside. But, seeing as Fruit of the 
Loom is a six-figure contributor to the RNC, and The Gap lags not far 
behind with a hefty five-figure donation, H.R. 553 may not be dead for 
long. 
<P>
 Yes, politics does make strange bedfellows, indeed. 
 <P>
 <P>
<i>Copyright 1995, Kathleen Howley<br>
Internet:73360.271@compuserve.com</i></body></html>
<p>
