</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>Pope John Paul II Come to America -- Howley</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center>
<h2>Pope John Paul II Comes to America </h2><p>
By<br>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/howley.html"> Kathleen Howley</a>
</center><hr><p> 
 

The arrival of Pope John Paul II makes me think, with a chuckle, about 
the last time his plane, nicknamed "Shepherd One," touched down on 
American soil. <p>

It was at Stapleton International Airport, in Denver, for the 
celebration of the 1993 World Youth Day. Then, as now, President Bill 
Clinton waited to greet the pontiff, arriving via Air Force One less 
than an hour before the pope. <p>

I was in the area reserved for the pack of journalists covering the 
event. As we waited for the arrival of the pope's plane, I discussed 
the story with a reporter from a Boston television station.  <p>

She told me, in a confidential tone, "He's not going to discuss 
abortion. I have it from a very good source."  <p>

I knew her source. No need to even say it. It was our own Raymond 
Flynn, hizzhonor, "Raybo," the former mayor of Boston. Despite his 
assignment to Rome, as the Clinton-appointed U.S. ambassador to the 
Vatican, Flynn and his staff still kept up connections with the Boston 
press corps. <p>

Boston journalists fondly refer to the former mayor as "Raybo," 
referring to the time, while mayor, when he ran -- Rambo-like -- into 
a burning building and carried out an elderly woman. The joke at the 
time was: Boston politicians will do anything to ensure another vote. <p>

Most Boston journalists tended to like the mayor, then and now, 
because he had all the trappings of a Irish Catholic politicians, with 
none of the baggage. Meaning, he used his religion to wring every last 
vote out of the predominantly Catholic populace, in true James Michael 
Curley fashion, but, he didn't support Church teaching with his vote, 
in true Kennedy fashion. <p>

Hizzhonor claimed to be personally opposed to abortion, yet he did 
everything in his power to elect our pro-abortion President Bill 
Clinton, who couldn't have won the White House without the Catholic 
vote. Flynn criss-crossed the country for months before the election, 
tirelessly campaigning for Clinton. <p>

And, in his own backyard, Flynn did nothing -- zero -- during his 
lengthy tenure as Boston's mayor to stop the hundreds of abortions 
going on in Boston City Hospital, which was under his control.  <p>

I shook my head, doubtfully.  <p>

"Naw, I think he's going to mention abortion," I said. "I think Raybo 
may be engaging in a bit of wishful thinking, on that one." <p>

My fellow journalist was confident.  <p>

"Nope. It's not going to come up, at least in public. I'd bet my last 
dollar on that," she said. <p>

Well, you know the outcome. It took the Holy Father all of three 
minutes to bring up the subject. In his arrival speech, on the airport 
tarmac, he exhorted Americans to "Defend life!"  <p>

Flynn, who on that occasion was holding the umbrella to shield Bill 
Clinton from the rain, looked more and more downcast, as the speech 
wore on. <p>

"All the great causes that are yours today will have meaning only to 
the extent that you guarantee the right to life and protect the human 
person," the Holy Father said, emphatically. <p>

At the time, I actually felt a bit sorry for our ambassador to the 
Vatican, as he stood in the rain with a dejected look on his face. It 
seems he tried to work some behind-the-scene angle that didn't, in the 
end, prove to be fruitful. <p>

You'd think the American media would be used to it by now, and expect 
John Paul to speak strongly about the issues that threaten modern 
society. After all, the Holy Father has often used his speeches to 
label abortion as "murder." <p>

Shocking, isn't it? In the stultifying atmosphere of today's American 
culture, everyone is supposed to toe the line. Even the Conservatives 
aren't willing to take a risk by accurately describing what happens 
during an abortion, or by verbalizing the forces that lie at the root 
of our anti-life society. <p>

Those who try to defend the modern status quo have worked to convince 
Americans that "words kill" -- particularly when referring to 
abortion. Of course, America is built on the premise that only free 
and robust debate will ensure our liberty. But, in large part, the 
other side has convinced most citizens that speaking too strongly on 
any issue is somehow a danger to us all. <p>

Ironically, the opposite is true. In truth, silence kills. 
Historically, we've seen what happens, again and again, when good 
people stay quiet.  <p>

We can all take a lesson from the Holy Father, who during all of his 
previous 67 trips outside the Vatican has never hesitated to speak the 
truth, with love. <p>

He doesn't flinch when condemning such things as chemical 
contraception, sterilization, en-vitro fertilization, feminist 
extremism, and sex outside of marriage, to name but a few hot button 
issues.  <p>

When was the last time an American leader had the guts to lay it on 
the line, like that? <p>

 
<i>Copyright 1995, Kathleen Howley <br>
Internet:73360.271@compuserve.com</i><p>
