<head>

<title>Rockwell: The Farm Trick Reform -- 04/17/96
</title>

</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<i>
 April 2, 1996
</I>
<h2> The Farm Trick Reform
</h2>



Llewellyn H. Rockwell, Jr.
<p>

Hillary Clinton should have called her medical bill "Freedom 
To Heal." Then Congress might have passed it as restoring the 
free market in medicine. If you don't believe such a trick would 
have worked, take a look at the "Freedom To Farm" bill now 
sailing into law. 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

Official propaganda says this bill restores a free market in 
agriculture, ending 60 years of subsidies and planning. But ask 
yourself: if this were really true, wouldn't farmers on the dole, 
and the media, be in hysterics? 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

Of course, and a close examination of the bill backs up this 
suspicion. The existing scheme, based on New Deal programs in 
turn modeled on the old Russian system, is retained in all its 
essentials. After this bill expires in seven years, the 1949 law 
that presently oppresses us will again be the law of the land. 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

Not that the new bill is salt peanuts. With a $47 billion 
price tag, it allocates even more money to subsidies initially, 
and to crazy new liberal programs. But in seven years, we're 
told, price supports and subsidies will be "phased out." 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

This farm bill is typical of a Congress that can't bring 
itself to cut a dime of federal spending, yet passes reams of 
"revolutionary" laws promising to cut, slash, abolish, and 
otherwise establish a libertarian Heaven on Earth...sometime in 
the next millennium. 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

But in the here and now, the bill retains price supports for 
peanuts and sugar, as well as price-fixing for milk. It renews a 
program locking up 36 million acres. And it throws away $1.4 
billion on more regulations, $200 million on a Florida swamp, and 
$300 million on "rural development." 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

All in all, this bill could have been written by Bill 
Clinton, which is why he's glad to sign it. The Democrats 
particularly like the food stamp and school lunch provisions. 
Why, you may ask, are these part of a farm bill? Because those
who benefit, along with the "poor," are wealthy agribusinessmen.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

Why this bill? Why now? Crop prices are at a ten-year high, 
and under the current subsidy formula, payments would be low. So, 
by merest happenstance, this bill changes the price-based system 
into a flat subsidy. Three to four billion dollars more will be 
spent for farm welfare immediately. 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

The bill's supporters say it eliminates many set asides, 
acreage controls, and crop mandates. But that would only be a 
glorious thing if the industry weren't subsidized and protected 
from competition. "Freedom to farm"--with other people's money.  
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

The farm program is one of the oldest federal scandals. The troubles
began a century and half ago, when U.S. tariffs were set 
to favor industry at the expense of agriculture. The policy 
culminated in an invasion of the agricultural South by former 
industrial lobbyist Abe Lincoln. 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

Then, in the first world war, the federal government pumped 
up the price of wheat and other products, and after the war, 
tried to keep them that way. That effort failed, and after two 
devastating post-war downturns, officials sought more 
protectionism and outright planning. 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

By the time of the Great Depression, the Jeffersonian ideal 
of the independent yeoman farmer was banished. As president, 
Herbert Hoover set out to keep prices high by subsidies, trade 
restrictions, and planting controls at the very time when market 
pressures were forcing them to fall. 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

But Mr. Hoover was small potatoes compared to farm dictator 
Franklin D. Roosevelt. As he forced farmers to slaughter their 
hogs and plow under their crops in order to raise prices, he was 
also flooding some of the world's best farm land for the 
Tennessee Valley Authority. 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

The "brain trust" that gave us those policies still runs 
agriculture. The sector has become a virtual ward of the state, 
with the feds holding more than half of all farm debt. There are 
still independent farmers, and they avoid Washington like the 
boll weevil. Agriculture is dominated by subsidized agribusiness, 
its lobbyists, and its pet politicians. 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

The victims of food socialism are consumers and taxpayers, 
who shell out billions directly and in the form of artificially 
high prices every year. Also harmed are the remaining independent 
farmers, whose livelihoods are threatened by subsidized 
competition. 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

That's why Congress should pass a real Freedom To Farm Act. 
It would abolish the whole of the existing system, and subject 
the sector to the same competition and price dictates that free 
industries face. Congress should also stop concocting tricky new 
ways to prop up big government with misnamed bills. 
<p><P>
<i>
Llewellyn H. Rockwell, Jr., is president of the Ludwig von Mises 
Institute in Auburn, Alabama.<i>

</blockquote></blockquote>




<P> <br><center>
