<html>
<head>

<title>Rockwell: The Standard Bearer Returns -- 04/16/96
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<i>
 April 16, 1996
</I>
<h2> The Standard Bearer Returns
</h2>
Llewellyn H. Rockwell, Jr.
<p>

Taxpayers, it's no time to despair. The anti-government   
revolt that swept the Democrats out of power in Congress is still   
on. But in the newest twist, the revolt has exposed the   
Republican establishment's own compromises with government power.   
  <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

The evidence comes from a dramatic political contest in the  
14th district of Texas. Former Congressman and intellectual  
firebrand Ron Paul won the Republican runoff for the House seat  
currently held by party switcher Greg Laughlin. The results have  
sent shock waves through Republican ruling circles.   
  <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

Though a Democrat only yesterday, Mr. Laughlin had money,  
media access, the endorsement of the Republican elite, and the  
use of the party's biggest guns. Dr. Paul, in contrast, was the  
outsider who gained a stunning 9-point victory by stressing his  
independence, ideals, and pristine record.   
  <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;


In Washington, the race became a loyalty test. The House  
leadership prevailed upon 53 high-ranking Congressmen to send  
contributions to the Laughlin campaign. The party dispatched its  
own ample funds, along with Newt Gingrich and Tom DeLay, the two  
George Bushes, and even Reagan-era leftover Ed Meese.  
  <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;


But bigshots couldn't muscle the voters in this largely   
rural district. The endorsements only confirmed Dr. Paul's claim   
not to be part of any machine. In fact, Phil Gramm's ads for the   
Laughlin campaign had to be pulled when they began to backfire.   
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

 
The Laughlin strategy assumed, without evidence, that voters   
trust the Republican leadership to tell them how to vote. But the   
bloom was already off that rose. Republicans have run Congress   
for more than a year, and taxes are still high, spending is   
higher, living standards continue to fall, and our liberties are   
just as imperiled.   
  <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;


When Mr. Laughlin switched from the Democrat Party, the   
Republican leadership put him on the Ways and Means Committee,  
the best seat in the House for buying and selling special favors.   
But an insider deal couldn't erase Mr. Laughlin's voting record,   
which was Clintonesque to the core. His switch was not   
ideological, of course, but political. Throw in the  Roll Call    
scoop that he is Washington's number one junket taker, and he   
became the personification of double-dealing politics.   
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

  
The party claimed to support Mr. Laughlin because it wanted   
to show that converts can win elections. But that doesn't explain   
the timing. The switch occurred only after Dr. Paul told the   
House leadership of his intention to run. The deeper truth is   
that the leadership wanted to keep Dr. Paul and his   
uncompromising approach at bay.     
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;


Dr. Paul's voting record is a portrait of courage and of   
unshakable devotion to liberty. He worked against taxes,   
spending, foreign wars, and pork-barrel projects, even in his own   
district. In the ratings of the National Taxpayers Union, he   
holds the all-time highest score.   
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

 
When he was in Congress before, Dr. Paul never hesitated to   
buck the party leadership and vote against its hidden tax   
increases and unbalanced budgets. He tossed special interest   
groups out of his office. And he resisted personal pressure from   
Ronald Reagan to vote for IMF subsidies and military pork.   
  <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;


Dr. Paul was the first politician in this century to   
introduce term-limits legislation, not just for politicians, but   
also for federal judges and bureaucrats. He was the first to call   
for the abolition of Congressional pensions, and refused to take   
part in that giveaway. He was the first to call for the BATF to   
be abolished. And thanks to his efforts on behalf of the gold   
standard, the U.S. now mints the best-looking gold coins in the   
world.   
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

 
He is an eloquent spokesman for states rights and individual   
liberties against federal intrusion, for sound money against   
inflation and other Fed manipulations, and for self government   
against centralized power. His foreign policy views are those of   
George Washington: trade with all and belligerence toward none.   
  <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;


Dr. Paul combines his idealistic political philosophy with   
an impressive technical knowledge of economics. He is an exponent   
of the Austrian School, and knows more about such subjects as   
business cycles and central banking than most working economists   
and any sitting member of Congress.   
  <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;


As a physician who has brought more than 4,000 babies into   
the world, he also knows that the biggest enemy the family has is   
our declining economy, thanks to excessive taxes and regulations.   
He knows that the government is also to blame for our failing   
educational system.   
  <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;


In his fight, Dr. Paul forged a coalition that included the   
religious right, economic libertarians, home schoolers, gun   
owners, land owners, businessmen, and anti-war isolationists.   
That is, people who want to be left alone by the government.  
  <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;


Ron Paul faces another hurdle in the general election. But   
if he makes it, he will once again be big government's biggest   
enemy in Washington. No wonder Republican power elites,   
especially those whose actions belie their rhetoric, are worried.  
  
<p><P>
<i>
Llewellyn H. Rockwell, Jr., is president of the Ludwig von Mises 
Institute in Auburn, Alabama.<i>

</blockquote></blockquote>

<P> <br><center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map">
<img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0">
</a></center>
<P>
