<head>
<title>The Peanut Shell Game</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center>
<h2>The Peanut Shell Game</h2>
</center>
<hr>
<b> By:  Thomas A. Schatz: President, Citizens Against Government Waste</b>
<p>   
Since the days of the Great Depression, American farming communities have lived under the umbrella of government subsidies.  These assistance measures, initiated because of unstable market conditions, create strong dependency as farmers cling to the benefits of government intervention.     
<p>  
As a result of these programs, the American farmer is enriched and capitalizes on his position, while substantially distorting the agricultural market.  Through quotas and government handouts, farmers receive above-market prices, crop failure relief, and engage in a feudalistic method of production.  For the taxpayer and consumer,   
agricultural subsidy programs increase prices and waste tax dollars through needless expenditures.   
<p>
Established in 1933 as part of the Agricultural Adjustment Act, the peanut subsidy program stabilized agricultural income through price supports and production control.  Subsidies were welcome because one-fourth of the U.S. population resided in rural areas and farm earnings were well below national average income statistics, constituting a mere 53 percent of a nonfarm family's salary.  In 1933, the Chairman   
of the House Agriculture Committee, Representative Marvin Jones (D-Texas), believed in the necessity of the bill, but noted that the President "would surrender such programs when the emergency (was) past."  In 1934, FDR's Secretary of Agriculture, Henry Wallace, said, "The present program for readjusting productive acreage to market requirements is admittedly but a temporary method of dealing with an emergency.  It could not be relied upon as a permanent means of keeping farm production in line with market requirements."   
<p>
The emergency is over and the dynamics of farming have changed.  The number of farms have decreased by 69 percent, from 6.8 million farms in 1935  to 2 million farms today.  More importantly, the average income of a farm family now exceeds $39,000, higher than a nonfarm family's average income.  With the number of farms decreasing and the stabilization of agricultural income, programs such as peanut   
subsidies are relics of a bygone era.    
<p>
Peanuts are an important political and financial cash crop in the South.  The "Peanut Belt" stretches from Tidewater, Virginia to the New Mexican plateau and produces 5 billion pounds of peanuts, with an estimated value of $1.4 billion.  The political consequences outweigh the financial when it comes to eradicating the peanut program.   
<p>
Administered through the USDA's Agricultural Stabilization and Conservation Service, the peanut program consists of two mandates. First, the program controls the domestic supply of peanuts through a  poundage quota system.  This Soviet-style regulatory approach sets limits on production and allocates who should produce the specified amount.  Second, by restraining the domestic supply through the quota   
system, the government sets a minimum selling price for all domestic sales.  With a domestic support price of $714 per ton compared to a  world price of $494 per ton, domestic prices are 44.5 percent higher than the average world market price.  Domestic buyers must pay this higher price.  Subsidies are in direct contrast to the American ideal of free trade, which embraces the lowest cost and most efficient   
producer.   
<p>
The federal government is merely evoking a feudalistic system that benefits a few large farms while suppressing the rest.  Although anyone can grow peanuts, only those who have quota land can grow peanuts for domestic, price-supported use.  Thus, non-quota owners must either rent land that is part of the quota system, or settle for   exportation at the world market price.  Seventy percent of quota  
holders rent their land to peanut farmers, making $208 million a year in rental fees without growing one single peanut.  Contrary to popular political folklore, small farmers are not benefiting from the peanut program.  Currently, 80 percent of the quotas to grow domestic peanuts are owned by 20 percent of peanut farmers.   
<p>
To arrive at the appropriate price support amount, the government uses  the national average production cost.  Based on increases in the prices paid by producers for commodities and services, interest, taxes, and wage rates, the government then deciphers an increased fair price without considering the costs of producing peanuts.  In an  absurd twist of fate, if peanut production costs drop, the fixedsupport price still might rise, based on the entire U.S. average of  production costs.  Historically, the gap between quota support prices and costs has increased every year.   
<p>
Government control does not stop at the quotas and price supports. The USDA uses these two prescriptions for further market interruptions.  First, under law, peanut farmers may sell their peanuts directly to the government instead of market buyers.    
Regardless of crop conditions, peanut farmers have a guaranteed buyer-- the federal government -- at or above the inflated domestic price.  If the government cannot sell all of the collected peanuts to the public sector, then the rest will be sold for oil or meal at substantially lower prices.  In the end, the government picks up the price difference between the high price support and the market price.   
<p> 
Money spent by both the consumer and the government is not worth these results.  Every American farmer deserves a free market in which to develop efficiency and gain market share through his own right, not a government-given quota.  According to the General Accounting Office, consumers spend an additional $513 million a year for peanut products such as Peanut Butter and Kung Pao Chicken, excessive profits   
transferred to the peanut producers.  In the long run, these high   prices will hurt the peanut industry as consumers look to other lower-priced products.  In 1990, there was a 10 percent drop in the food industry's demand for peanuts.    
<p>
The $119 million spent by the federal government on the peanut program annually doesn't even take into account the administrative fees. The  price tag for the peanut program exceeds $200 million when administrative costs are calculated.     
<p>
This subsidy must end.  Consumers and taxpayers must not foot the bill   for this absurd manipulation of our strong hallowed market economy. This shell game of peanut subsidies must be cracked wide open and stopped.   
<p>
Yes, I want to join the more than 600,000 members of CAGW to fight Washington's wasteful ways.  I understand that $1.00 of my  contribution entitles me to four issues of Government WasteWatch.   
<p> 
I have enclosed my check made payable to CAGW in the amount of:   
<p>
<pre>_____ $15  _____ $25  _____ $50  _____ $100  _____ Other   
   
   
 Name_______________________________________________________   
 Address____________________________________________________   
