that the CPI overestimates the  increase in the cost of living from 0.7 to 2.0 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 4 -->  percentage points. This in turn
has misled Members of Congress and President Clinton  into thinking that GDP,
productivity, and real  wages have grown more slowly than they really  have.
Indeed, without the upward bias in the CPI, real wages would have grown
significantly  since 1983 instead of stagnating.
